Here are both approaches for Shell navigation in .NET MAUI.

**1. Register the route:**

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute("ProductDetailsPage", typeof(ProductDetailsPage));
```

**2. Navigate from ProductListPage (both approaches):**

```csharp
// Approach A — pass product ID as a string query parameter
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"ProductDetailsPage?productId={product.Id}");

// Approach B — pass the full Product object via a dictionary
var navParams = new Dictionary<string, object>
{
    { "product", selectedProduct }   // complex object
};
await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("ProductDetailsPage", navParams);
```

**3. Receive data in the ViewModel with `IQueryAttributable`:**

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    private string _productId;
    private Product _product;

    public string ProductId
    {
        get => _productId;
        set => SetProperty(ref _productId, value);
    }

    public Product Product
    {
        get => _product;
        set => SetProperty(ref _product, value);
    }

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach A — simple string parameter
        if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var id))
        {
            ProductId = id.ToString();
            // load full product from a service, etc.
        }

        // Approach B — full object passed via dictionary
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product p)
        {
            Product = p;
            ProductId = p.Id;
        }
    }
}
```

**4. Wire the ViewModel to the page:**

```csharp
public partial class ProductDetailsPage : ContentPage
{
    public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        BindingContext = vm;
    }
}
```

**Key differences:**

| | String query param | Dictionary object |
|---|---|---|
| **Syntax** | `$"route?key={val}"` | `GoToAsync("route", dict)` |
| **Data type** | strings only | any object |
| **In `ApplyQueryAttributes`** | value is `string` | value is original type — cast it |
| **Use when** | simple IDs, flags | you already have the object in memory |

Both approaches arrive in the same `ApplyQueryAttributes` method, so you can handle them side-by-side as shown above.
